Asa was the father of Jehoshaphat. Jehoshaphat was the father of Joram. Joram was the father of Uzziah.
Uzziah was the father of Jotham. Jotham was the father of Ahaz. Ahaz was the father of Hezekiah.
Hezekiah was the father of Manasseh. Manasseh was the father of Amon. Amon was the father of Josiah.
And Josiah was the father of Johanan and his brethren. In those days the Jews were carried away captive to Babylon.
Then the family line continued through Jeconiah, the father of Shealtiel, who was the father of Zerubbabel.
Zerubbabel was the father of Abiud. Abiud was the father of Eliakim. Eliakim was the father of Azor.
Azor was the father of Zadok. Zadok was the father of Achimaas. Achimaas was the father of Azareel.
Eliud was the father of Eleazar. Eleazar was the father of Matthan. Matthan was the father of Jacob.
Jacob was the father of Joseph. Joseph was the husband of Mary. And Mary gave birth to Jesus, who is called the Christ.
So there were fourteen generations from Abraham to David, fourteen generations from David to the exile to Babylon, and fourteen generations from the exile to Babylon to the Christ. The birth of Jesus Christ
This is how the birth of Jesus Christ came about: His mother Mary was pledged to be married to Joseph, but before they came together, she was found to be with child through the Holy Spirit.
Her husband, Youssef, was a pious man. He didn't want to humiliate her in public. So he planned to divorce her quietly.
But while Joseph was considering this, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream and said, "Joseph son of David, do not be afraid to take Mary as your wife, for the child conceived in her is from the Holy Spirit."
You will give birth to a son. You must name him Jesus, because he will save his people from their sins.
All this was to fulfill what the Lord had spoken by the prophet,
"Therefore the Lord himself will give you a sign. Behold, the virgin shall conceive and bear a son, and shall call his name Immanuel;" (Isaiah 7:14) The name Immanuel means "God with us."
Joseph woke up and did as the angel of the Lord commanded him. He took Mary as his wife.
But he had no union with her until she gave birth to a son. And he gave the name Jesus to the child.
Two wise women visit Jesus.
Jesus was born in Bethlehem in Judea. This happened during the reign of King Herod. After the birth of Jesus, wise men from the east came to Jerusalem.
They asked, "Where is the king of the Jews born? For we saw his star in the east and have come to worship him."
When King Herod heard this, he was greatly disturbed, and all Jerusalem with him.
So Herod summoned the chief priests and teachers of the law and asked them where the Messiah was to be born.
"In Bethlehem in Judah," they answered. "This is what the prophet wrote:
"But you, Bethlehem Ephrathah, though you are small among the clans of Judah, yet out of you will come for me one who will be ruler over Israel, whose origins are from of old, from ancient times." (Micah 5:2)
Then Herod secretly called the wise men and learned from them the exact time the star had appeared.
Send them to Bethlehem. He said, "Go! Search carefully for the child. As soon as you find him, bring me a report. Then I too can go and worship him."
After the wise men had listened to the king, they set out on their way. And the star they had seen in the east went ahead of them until it stopped over the place where the child was.
When they saw the star, joy filled them.
The wise men went to the house. There they saw the child with his mother Mary. They knelt down and worshiped him. Then they opened their treasures. They gave him gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
But God warned them in a dream not to return to Herod. So they returned to their country by another road. The flight of Jesus' family into Egypt.
When the wise men had departed, Joseph had a dream. In the dream an angel of the Lord appeared to him. "Get up!" the angel said. "Take the child and his mother and escape to Egypt. Stay there until I tell you to return, for Herod is going to search for the child to kill him."
Joseph woke up. That night, he took the child and his mother Mary and left for Egypt.
So they remained there until Herod died. And this was to fulfill what the Lord had spoken by the prophet, saying, “Out of Egypt have I called My Son” (Jeremiah 11:1).
Herod realized that the wise men had deceived him. He became furious. He issued orders regarding Bethlehem and the surrounding area. All male children two years old and under were killed. This was in accordance with the time that the wise men had seen the star.
In this way the words of the prophet Jeremiah were fulfilled, who said,
"A voice is heard in Ramah, a voice of weeping and great mourning. Rachel is weeping for her children; she refuses to be comforted, because they are no more." (Jeremiah 31:15) The return of Jesus' family to Nazareth.
After Herod's death, Joseph had a dream while he was still in Egypt. In the dream, an angel of the Lord appeared to him.
The angel said, "Arise, take the child and his mother, and go to the land of Israel, for those who sought the child's life are dead."
So Joseph rose and took the child and his mother, Mary, to the land of Israel.
But when he heard that Archelaus was reigning over Judea in place of his father Herod, he was afraid to go there. And being warned in a dream, he withdrew to the region of Galilee.
There he lived in a town called Nazareth. Thus what was spoken by the prophets about Jesus was fulfilled. They said, "He will be called a Nazarene."
John the Baptist prepares the way.
In those days John the Baptist came, preaching in the wilderness of Judea.
He said, "Cease your sins, for the Angel of Death is near."
John is the one of whom the prophet Isaiah spoke. He said, "A voice cries out: 'In the wilderness prepare the way of the Lord, make straight in the desert a highway for our God.'" (Isaiah 40:3)
John's clothes were made of camel hair. He had a leather belt around his waist. His food was locusts and wild honey.
People went out to him from Jerusalem and all Judea and the entire region of the Jordan.
When they confessed their sins, John baptized them in the Jordan River.
John saw many Pharisees and Samaritans coming to where he was baptizing. He said to them, "You brood of vipers! Who warned you to flee from the wrath to come?"
Bear fruit in keeping with repentance.
Do not think that you can say to yourselves, "We have Abraham as our father." I tell you that out of these stones God can raise up children for Abraham.
The shovel is already at the roots of the trees. All trees that do not produce good fruit will be cut down. They will be thrown into the fire.
I baptize you with water for repentance, but after me comes one who is mightier than I, and I am not worthy to untie the thong of his sandals. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire.
"His winnowing fork is in his hand to clear his threshing floor and to gather the wheat into his barn, but the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire." - Jesus
Jesus came from Galilee to the Jordan River. He wanted to be baptized by John.
But John tried to prevent him, saying to Jesus, "I need to be baptized by you. Why do you come to me?"
Jesus answered, "Let it be so now; it is right for us to do this, to fulfill all righteousness." Then John consented.
As soon as Jesus was baptized, he came up out of the water. At that moment the sky opened, and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove and coming to him.
A voice from heaven said, "This is my Son, whom I love; with him I am well pleased."
Jesus tempts
The Spirit led Jesus into the wilderness, where he was tempted by the devil.
After 40 days and 40 nights of fasting, Jesus was hungry.
The tempter came to him and said, "If you are the Son of God, command these stones to become loaves of bread."
Jesus answered, "It is written: 'Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that comes from the mouth of God.'" (Deuteronomy 8:3)
Then Satan took Jesus to the holy city and set him on the pinnacle of the temple.
"If you are the Son of God," he said, "throw yourself down, for it is written: 'He will command his angels concerning you, and they will lift you up in their hands, so that you will not strike your foot against a stone.'" (Psalm 91:11-12)
Jesus answered, "It is written: 'Do not put the Lord your God to the test'" (Deuteronomy 6:16).
Finally, the devil took Jesus to a very high mountain. He showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory.
"If you bow down and worship me," he said, "I will give you all this."
Jesus said to him, "Get behind me, Satan! For it is written, 'You shall worship the Lord your God and him only shall you serve.'" (Deuteronomy 6:13)
Then the devil left Jesus, and angels came and attended to him. Jesus began to preach in the synagogues.
John was put in prison. And when Jesus heard of it, he withdrew into Galilee.
Jesus left Nazareth and made his home in Capernaum by the lake, in the region of Zebulun and Naphali.
In this way, what the prophet Isaiah said was fulfilled. He said,
"Land of Zebulun! Land of Naphtali! Galilee, where the Gentiles live! Land along the Mediterranean Sea! Region east of the Jordan River!"
"For those who live in darkness will see a great light. They live in the land of deep darkness, but a light will shine on them." (Isaiah 9:1,2)
From that time Jesus began to preach, and to say, "Repent: for the kingdom of heaven is at hand." Jesus chooses the first disciples.
One day Jesus was walking along the shore of Lake Galilee. There he saw two brothers. They were fishermen. One was called Simon Peter, and the other Andrew. They were casting their net into the lake.
"Come, follow me," Jesus said, "and I will make you fishers of men."
So they left their nets at once and followed him.
From there, he saw two other brothers, James son of Zebedee and his brother John. They were in a boat with their father Zebedee, mending their nets. Jesus called out to them.
When they heard about him, they went out to meet him, and left their boats and their father, following Jesus. Jesus healed the sick people.
Jesus went throughout Galilee, teaching in their synagogues, preaching the good news of the Kingdom, and healing every disease and sickness among the people.
The news about him spread all over Syria. People came to him from everywhere, bringing all kinds of sick people. Some were suffering from severe pains. Others were possessed by demons. Some were trembling violently. Others were completely paralyzed. Jesus healed them all.
Large crowds followed him. Some people came from Galilee, and from the Decapolis, and from Jerusalem and Judea, and others from beyond the Jordan.
Jesus gives blessings.
Jesus saw the crowds and went up a mountain and sat down. His disciples came to him.
Then he began to teach them. He said,
"Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be filled with the kingdom of heaven."
Blessed are those who are sad, for they shall be comforted by God.
Blessed are the dreamers. They will be cast into the earth.
Blessed are those with pure hearts and minds that strive for what is right, for they shall find their true home in Him.
Blessed is the Most Merciful of those who show mercy. Mercy is for those who show mercy.
Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they will be called children of God.
Blessed are those who are persecuted because of righteousness, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
"Blessed are you when people ridicule you and persecute you because of me. Blessed are you when they say all kinds of evil against you because of me."
Rejoice and be glad. Your reward in heaven is great. Likewise, people harmed the prophets who lived long ago. Salt and light.
"You are the salt of the earth. But if salt loses its saltiness, how can it be made salty again? It is no longer good for anything, except to be thrown out and trampled underfoot."
You are the light of the world. A city built on a hill cannot be hidden.
Also, people do not light a lamp and put it under a bushel basket. Instead, they put it on its stand. Then it shines for everyone in the house.
"In the same way, let your light shine before others, so that they may see your good works and give glory to your Father who is in heaven. Jesus gives full meaning to the law."
Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them.
What I am telling you is true. Heaven and earth will pass away before the smallest letter or stroke of the Law disappears. Not the smallest letter or stroke of the Law will disappear until everything is accomplished.
Do not neglect one of the least of these commandments. And do not teach others to violate them. For if you do, you will be called least in the kingdom of heaven. But practice and teach these commandments. Then you will be called great in the kingdom of heaven.
This is what I tell you: You must be more righteous than the Pharisees and the teachers of the law. If you are not, you will surely not enter the kingdom of heaven. Murder.
"You have heard what was said to the people in times past: 'Do not murder' (Exodus 20:13). Every murderer will be subject to murder."
But this is what I say: Do not be angry with your brother. Whoever is angry with his brother will be subject to judgment. Again, whoever says to his brother, 'You fool!' will be in danger of the fire of hell.
"Suppose you are offering your gift at the altar and there remember that your brother has something against you."
Leave your gift there before the altar. Go first and be reconciled with your brother. Then come and present your gift.
"Suppose someone has a claim against you and takes you to court. Settle the matter quickly. Do it while you are still with him on the way. If you don't, he may hand you over to the judge. The judge may hand you over to the officer, and you may be thrown into prison."
What I'm telling you is true. You're not leaving until you pay the last penny! Bastard.
"You have heard that it was said, 'Do not commit adultery.' (Exodus 20:14)
But I say to you, whoever looks at a woman to lust after her has already committed adultery with her in his heart.
"If your right eye causes you to sin, gouge it out and throw it away. For it is better that you lose one of your members than that your whole body be thrown into hell.
"If your right hand causes you to sin, cut it off and throw it away. It is better for you to lose one part of your body than for your whole body to be thrown into hell. Mark 9:43"
They said, "O Moses, indeed some of the people take their wives as mothers, and others treat their wives cruelly. And if they divorce them, they will find no harm in them, and if they keep them, they will find no benefit. So teach us what is right in this matter."
But that is what I say: Whoever divorces his wife causes her to commit adultery, and whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery. A man must not divorce his wife except for marital unfaithfulness. I tell you this under oath.
"And again, you have heard what was said to his people long ago: 'Do not break the covenant you made with the Lord. Keep the promises you swore to him.'"
But that's what I'm telling you. Don't make any such promise at all. Don't make it in the name of heaven. It's God's throne.
Do not make it in the name of the Earth, for it is the footstool of God's feet. Nor make it in the name of Jerusalem, for it is the city of the great King.
Do not swear by your heads, you cannot make a single hair white or black.
Just let "yes" mean "yes." And let "no" mean "no." Anything more than this is from the devil. Be kind to others.
"You have heard that it was said, 'An eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth' (Exodus 21:24; Leviticus 24:20; Deuteronomy 19:21)"
But this is what I say: Do not resist an evil person. If anyone slaps you on the right cheek, turn to them the other cheek also.
If anyone takes you to court and wants your shirt, let him have your coat as well.
Suppose someone forces you to walk one mile. Go two miles with him.
"Give to those who ask you. Do not hate those who use you. Love your enemies."
"You have heard that it was said, 'Love your neighbor and hate your enemy.'"
But that is what I say: Love your enemies. Pray for those who mistreat you.
"Therefore you shall be perfect, just as your Father in heaven is perfect. "He makes His sun rise on the evil and on the good, and sends rain on the just and on the unjust.
"If you only love those who love you, what reward do you get? Even tax collectors do that."
If you only greet your own people, what more are you doing than others? Even unbelievers do that.
Therefore you are to be perfect, as your heavenly Father is perfect.
Giving to the poor
"Beware of practicing your righteousness before other people in order to be seen by them; otherwise you will have no reward from your Father who is in heaven. Thus, when you give to the needy, do not publicize it as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and on the streets, so that they may be honored by others. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward in full. But when you give to the needy, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing, so that your giving may be in secret; and your Father who sees in secret will reward you."
"When you give, do not announce it with words or be ostentatious with your wealth. Do not be like those who take disbelievers as allies instead of believers. If anyone does that, he is not of you, and he is a wrongdoer. A believer should not take a disbeliever as a close friend, even if the disbeliever is related to him in the religion. Say, 'The right guidance is from Allah.' If they come to you persistently, do not be persistent with them. Have you known that they are disbelievers and that Allah will replace them with others? Do not think that Allah is unaware of the actions of the wrongdoers. He is only giving them respite until the Day when eyes will stare in horror. You cannot escape in the land or distance yourself from the disobedient."
"When you give to the poor, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing."
Then your charity will be in secret. Your Father who sees in secret will reward you. He sees what you do in secret. Prayer
"When you pray, do not be like the hypocrites who love to be seen by people, making their prayers a spectacle. They stand up from a sitting position just to be noticed. They are told to stand, but they only sit for
"When you pray, enter the mosques of God, for God delights in the righteous. God is near, responsive. He knows what the hearts conceal."
"When you pray, do not be like the hypocrites who say to their brothers, who were turning away from them in secret, 'I am with you.' They only say this to be seen by people. And do not be like those who say, 'We are praying.' Tell them, 'Fear God. Indeed, God is severe in punishment.'"
Do not be like them. Your father knows what you need even before you ask him.
"This is how you should pray: 'Our Father in heaven, hallowed be your name.
Thy kingdom come. Thy will be done on earth as it is in heaven.
Give us our daily bread.
Forgive us our sins, as we forgive those who have wronged us.
"Save us from falling into sin when we are tempted. And protect us from the accursed Satan."
Forgive people their sins, and your Heavenly Father will forgive you.
But if you do not forgive people their offenses, neither will your Father forgive your offenses. - Fasting
"When you fast, do not be like the hypocrites, who are false to themselves. They proclaim their fasting loudly, so do not be like them. But say, 'We intend to fast,' and when you are forbidden, 'We refrain.' That is better for you. Allah is Forgiving and Merciful."
"But if you keep silent, anoint your heads with oil and wash your faces."
Then none will know that you are fasting except your Lord, Who is in the heavens. Your Lord is not unaware of what you do. As for the first group, they do not know that you have become among them in the morning.
"Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moths and vermin destroy, and where thieves break in and steal.
But store up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust destroys, and where thieves do not break in or steal.
Your heart will be where your treasure is.
"The eye is like a lamp for the body. If your eyes are good, your whole body will be full of light."
But suppose your eyes are weak. Then your whole body will be dark. And if the light within you is darkness, how great is that darkness!
No one can serve two masters at the same time. He will hate one and love the other. Or he will be devoted to one and despise the other. You cannot serve God and money at the same time. Do not be anxious.
I tell you, do not be anxious about your life, what you shall eat or what you shall drink, nor about your body, what you shall put on. Is not life more than food, and the body more than clothing?
"Look at the birds of the air; they do not sow or reap or store away in barns, and yet your heavenly Father feeds them. Are you not much more valuable than they?"
Can you add an hour to your life by worrying?
"Why do you worry about your clothes? Look at how the wild flowers grow. They do not work or spin clothes.
But that is what I tell you. Not even Solomon in all his glory was clothed like one of these.
"If God so clothes the grass of the field, which today is alive and tomorrow is thrown into the oven, will he not much more clothe you, O you of little faith?"
So do not worry, saying, ‘What will we eat?’ or ‘What will we drink?’ or ‘What will we wear?’
People who don't believe in God chase after all those things. Your Father in heaven knows you need them.
"But seek first the kingdom of God, and all these things will be added to you."
"Therefore do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow will worry about itself. Each day has enough trouble of its own."
Be fair in your judgments of others.
Do not judge people, lest you be judged.
You will be judged by the same standard by which you judge others. You will be measured by the same measure with which you measure others.
You see a splinter of feather in your friend's eye, but you don't care about the beam in your own eye.
How do you tell your friend: "Let me take this piece of wood out of your eye," while there's a piece of wood in your own eye?
You hypocrite! First remove the beam from your own eye. Then you will see clearly to remove the speck from your friend's eye.
"Do not give what is holy to the dogs; nor cast your pearls before swine, lest they trample them under their feet, and turn and tear you in pieces. Ask, seek, knock."
Ask and it will be given to you; seek and you will find; knock and the door will be opened to you.
To everyone who asks, it will be given. To everyone who searches, it will be found. To everyone who knocks, it will be opened.
"If your son asks for bread, which one of you would give him a stone?"
Or were you to ask them to give you a fish, who among you would stand up to him with a miracle?
Even if you are evil, you know how to give good gifts to your children. How much more will your Father who is in heaven give good things to those who ask Him!
"In everything, do to others what you would want them to do to you; this is the Law and the Prophets."
Enter the kingdom of God through the narrow gate. For wide is the gate and broad is the road that leads to destruction and hell. Many enter through that gate.
But the gate is small and the way is narrow that leads to life. Few find it. A tree and its fruit.
Beware of false prophets, which come to you in sheep's clothing, but inwardly they are ravening wolves.
You can tell what they really are by what they do. "Do people gather grapes from thorns? Do they pluck figs from thistles?"
In the same way, every good tree bears good fruit, but the bad tree bears bad fruit.
A good tree cannot bear bad fruit, and a bad tree cannot bear good fruit.
Every tree that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire.
A tree is known by its fruit.
Not everyone who says to me, 'Lord, Lord,' will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only the one who does the will of my Father who is in heaven.
Many will say to me on that day, 'Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name? Did we not cast out demons in your name? Did we not do many miracles in your name?'
Then I will inform them, "I did not know you." Say, "Indeed, I am to you a messenger from Allah, and [even] if you disbelieve, [O Muhammad], it is to Allah that what is in the heavens and earth belongs, and Allah is All-Knowing over what you do."
"Therefore everyone who hears these words of mine and puts them into practice is like a wise man who built his house on the rock."
The sky rains. The waters rise. The winds blow and strike that house. But it does not fall. It is built on the rock.
But everyone who hears my words and does not put them into practice is like a foolish man who built his house on the sand.
The sky rains. The water rises. The wind blows and hits that house. And it falls with a loud noise.
Jesus finished saying all these things. The crowds were amazed at his teaching.
He taught as one having authority, not as the scribes.
Jesus heals a man with a skin disease.
Jesus came down from the mountain. Large crowds followed him.
A man with a skin disease came to Jesus, knelt down, and said, "Lord, if you choose, you can make me clean."
Jesus reached out his hand and touched the man, saying, "I want to do this. Be 'clean'!" Immediately the man was cleansed of his leprosy.
Then Jesus said to him, "Do not tell anyone. Go, show yourself to the priest and offer the gift that Moses commanded, as a testimony to them." The faith of a Roman centurion.
When Jesus came to Capernaum, a Roman centurion approached him and pleaded for his help.
"Oh Lord," he said, "my servant is bedridden and cannot move. He is in great distress."
Jesus said, "I will go and heal him."
Then the centurion said, "Lord, do not trouble yourself, for I am not worthy to have you come under my roof. But only speak a word, and my servant will be healed.
I myself am a man under authority, and I have soldiers under me: and I say to this man, Go, and he goes; and to another, Come, and he comes; and to my servant, Do this, and he does it.
When Jesus heard this, he marveled and said to those who followed him, "Truly I tell you, I have not found anyone in Israel with faith like this."
"I tell you, many will come from the east and the west, and will take their places at the feast with Abraham, Isaac and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven."
But whoever says, 'I am in his kingdom,' will be cast out into the darkness. There will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
Then Jesus said to the Roman soldiers, "Go, and it will be as you have believed." And his servant was healed at that very moment. Jesus healed many.
When Jesus came into Peter's house, he saw Peter's wife's mother lying in bed with a fever.
Jesus touched her hand, and the fever left her. She got up and began to serve him.
When evening came, many who were demon-possessed were brought to him, and he drove out the spirits with a word and healed all the sick.
He did it to fulfill what the prophet Isaiah said: "He bore our sins on his shoulders—sicknesses that should have been ours." (Isaiah 53:4) Following Jesus is costly.
Seeing the crowd, Jesus gave orders to cross to the other side of Lake Galilee.
Then one of the scribes came forward and said to him, "Teacher, I will follow you wherever you go."
Jesus answered, "Foxes have holes, and birds of the air have nests, but the Son of Man has no place to lay his head."
Another of his followers said to him, "Lord, first let me go and bury my father."
But Jesus said to him, "Follow me. Let the dead bury their own dead." Jesus silences the storm.
Jesus got into a boat. His disciples followed him.
Suddenly a fierce storm swept over the lake. The waves crashed against the boat. But Jesus was asleep.
So the disciples woke him up, saying, "Master, save us! We are perishing!"
And he said to him, "O you of little faith! Why do doubts rise in your heart?" Then Jesus got up and commanded the winds and the sea, and there was a great calm.
So the disciples were amazed and asked, "Who is this man? Even the winds and the sea obey him!" Jesus heals two men who were possessed by demons.
Jesus arrived on the other side of the lake in the region of the Gerasenes. Two men possessed by demons met him. They had come out of the tombs. The men were so violent that no one could pass by.
"Son of God, what do you want with us?" they cried. "Have you come to punish us before our time of judgment?"
Not far away, there was a large herd of pigs eating.
The demons begged Jesus, "If you drive us out, send us to the pigs in the field."
Jesus said to them, "Go!" And the unclean spirits came out of the men and entered into the swine, and the herd ran violently down the steep place into the sea, about two thousand of them, and were drowned in the sea.
Those who were tending the pigs fled and told it in the city and in the country. The people went out to see what had happened, and they came to Jesus and found the men from whom the demons had gone out, sitting at his feet, clothed and in their right mind; and they were afraid.
Then he went out from the city to meet Jesus. And when they saw him, they begged him to leave the mountain where they were, because their city was near.
Jesus heals a man who cannot walk.
Jesus got into a boat and crossed the water to the other side of the wilderness, arriving at his hometown.
Some men came, carrying a paralyzed man on a mat. When Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralyzed man, "Take heart, son; your sins are forgiven."
Then some of the religious scholars said, "He is saying something very corrupting!"
Jesus knew what they were thinking and said, "Why are you thinking these evil thoughts?"
Is it easier to say, "Your sins are forgiven," or to say, "Get up and walk"?
I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins." Then he spoke to the man who couldn't walk. "Get up," he said. "Take your mat and go to your home."
